Off-target suppression for netsnmp-smux-rreq-uaf.

The agent's off-target crash is a heap-buffer-overflow at agent/agent_trap.c:570
(`convert_v2pdu_to_v1`), READ of size 8 (one `oid`) — DISTINCT from the preset
heap-use-after-free (smux RReq DELETE path) at agent/agent_handler.c:350.

Root cause (off-target): on the v2->v1 trap conversion path, the code compares
the snmpTrapOID value (`vblist->val.objid`) against `trap_prefix`, passing
OID_LENGTH(trap_prefix) as the SOURCE length regardless of the value's actual
length. When the attacker supplies a snmpTrapOID whose objid is exactly
OID_LENGTH(trap_prefix) elements long (72 bytes = 9 oids) and equal to the
standard prefix, snmp_oid_compare matches, and the "standard trap" branch then
dereferences `vblist->val.objid[OID_LENGTH(trap_prefix)]` (index 9) — one element
past the end of the 72-byte allocation -> heap-buffer-overflow.

Fix (minimal bounds guard): only take the standard-trap branch when the actual
objid length strictly exceeds OID_LENGTH(trap_prefix), so the [OID_LENGTH] access
is in-bounds. Shorter snmpTrapOID values fall through to the enterprise-specific
branch, which already guards `len <= 2` and accesses only objid[len-1]. No logic
change for well-formed traps (objid longer than the prefix). The preset UAF path
(smux_rreq_process -> smux_replace_active -> netsnmp_unregister_handler) is on an
unrelated SMUX-registration code path and is unaffected.

--- a/agent/agent_trap.c
+++ b/agent/agent_trap.c
@@ -559,8 +559,9 @@ convert_v2pdu_to_v1( netsnmp_pdu* template_v2pdu )
      *    and the enterprise field from the v2 varbind list.
      * If there's an agentIPAddress varbind, set the agent_addr too
      */
-    if (!snmp_oid_compare(vblist->val.objid, OID_LENGTH(trap_prefix),
-                          trap_prefix,       OID_LENGTH(trap_prefix))) {
+    if ((vblist->val_len / sizeof(oid)) > OID_LENGTH(trap_prefix) &&
+        !snmp_oid_compare(vblist->val.objid, OID_LENGTH(trap_prefix),
+                          trap_prefix,       OID_LENGTH(trap_prefix))) {
         /*
          * For 'standard' traps, extract the generic trap type
          *   from the snmpTrapOID value, and take the enterprise
